sections.body:
A wet bath is particles riding in a liquid **vehicle**, and the vehicle has a specification of its own. It must:

- be **low viscosity**, so particles migrate quickly to weak leakage fields — light petroleum vehicles are typically limited to about 3 cSt at 100 °F;
- **wet the surface completely** — a film that beads or breaks leaves uninspected streaks;
- be **chemically inert** to parts and platings;
- show **minimal inherent fluorescence**, color, and odor;
- survive a recirculating pump, shift after shift.

**Oil vehicles** are refined light distillates selected for exactly those properties plus a flash point high enough for safety — commonly specified around 200 °F (93 °C) or higher. **Water vehicles** are cheaper, nonflammable, and fast-wetting — but only with conditioning: **wetting agents** to spread the film (verified by a water-break check), **corrosion inhibitors** to protect parts and tank, and **antifoam agents** so agitation does not whip suds that trap particles.

**Temperature needs.** Wet baths generally stay below about **135 °F (57 °C)** — hotter surfaces cook off carrier, degrade fluorescent dyes, and with water can flash to steam. Hot work belongs to **dry powder**, with some powders rated to roughly **600 °F (316 °C)**. Cold bites the other way: viscosity climbs, particle migration slows, and water baths in field trucks can freeze — so shops add freeze protection or switch to oil for winter work.
